@MicahZoltu @holiman : ok. I've got the point why this is dangerous. 

Just for the reference @flygoing, made a good comment on this in #909 (it could work, if we would have rent based storage).

Ok, I am closing this ticket. I learned a lot! Thank you very much for your time and comments.

Some fresh ideas from Gitter: If refund would be disabled for SCLONEd contracts, SCLONE couldn't be used for DoS. 

@Arachnid is pointing out that this would require storing the information about if the contract was cloned or not, which would be a big change in the state trie. Moreover, Parity could have a problem with cloning, because it is keeping each storage trie isolated from each other. It's not a graph like in geth.

Moreover @holiman is concerned that storage trie could be bloated by cloning and making minor changes to the state. I think this shouldn't be a problem, since SSTORE as used today would cause the same changes in the existing tries.

@Agusx1211 You can already achieve that with an oracle.

The only difference from that would be that you could get other contract storage's contents during a "same transaction" context (as opposed to another transaction's context with an oracle).

Do you know of a design where this is an actual vulnerability, though? (i.e. where the actual encapsulation of `private` storage vars is essential to a contract's design)

Here is a competing straw man proposal that addresses the use case that SCLONE is trying to solve and does not have the gas problem.

---

# SLOADANY

> '<sub>s</sub>[0]  [<sub>s</sub>[1]]<sub>s</sub><sub>s</sub>[0]

And you would use this like:

```solidity
function f(uint word, uint account) public returns (uint value) {
    assembly {
        value := sloadany(word, account))
    }
}
```

Then the higher-level Solidity might look like this:

```solidity
interface EIP721V2 {
    function tokens() returns (uint[]);
}

contract ColorInspector {
    function firstYellowToken(EIP721V2 contract) returns (uint) {
        uint[] tokens = contract.tokens;
        for ...
            if (isYellow(tokens[i]))
                return tokens[i];
    }
}
```

# Discussion

* This is a O(1) operation. 
* The Entriken attack above does not work -- if the underlying storage is gone (and partially refunded) then you can't access it any more.
